  "Allegations" : "SEC LITIGATION RELEASE NO. 19144 DATED MARCH 17, 2005; THE SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (THE \"COMMISSION\") ANNOUNCED THAT ON MARCH 17, 2005, IT FILED A COMPLAINT IN THE UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT FOR THE DISTRICT OF MASSACHUSETTS AGAINST STEVEN A. GILMAN (\"S. GILMAN\"), ANOTHER INDIVIDUAL AND COMPANIES THEY OPERATED, COLLECTIVELY (THE \"DEFENDANTS\") ALLEGING THAT THEY CONDUCTED AN OFFERING FRAUD AND MISAPPROPRIATED APPROXIMATELY $14 MILLION OF INVESTOR PROCEEDS. THE COMPLAINT ALLEGES THAT THE DEFENDANTS VIOLATED SECTION 17(A) OF THE SECURITIES ACT OF 1933 (\"SECURITIES ACT\") AND SECTION 10(B) OF THE SECURITIES EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934 (\"EXCHANGE ACT\") AND RULE 10B-5 THEREUNDER. THE COMMISSION'S COMPLAINT ALLEGES THE DEFENDANTS AIDED AND ABETTED VIOLATIONS SECTION 15(A) OF THE EXCHANGE ACT AND SECTIONS 206(1) AND 206(2) OF THE INVESTMENT ADVISERS ACT OF 1940 AND SECTION 15(C) OF THE EXCHANGE ACT. THE COMPLAINT ALLEGES THAT BETWEEN DECEMBER 1998 AND OCTOBER 2003, THE DEFENDANTS SOLICITED APPROXIMATELY $20 MILLION FROM 40 PEOPLE WHO INVESTED FUNDS WITH AN UNREGISTERED BROKER DEALER AND INVESTMENT ADVISER. ACCORDING TO THE COMPLAINT, THE DEFENDANTS FUNNELED INVESTOR PROCEEDS TO THEIR PERSONAL USE THROUGH, A REGISTERED BROKER-DEALER.",
